HEADWORD: Prolusion
<hw>Pro*lu"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>prolusio</ets>, fr. <ets>proludere</ets> to prelude; <ets>pro</ets>
before + <ets>ludere</ets> to play: cf. F. <ets>prolusion</ets>, It.
<ets>prolusione</ets>.]</ety> <def>A trial before the principal
performance; a prelude; hence, an introductory essay or exercise.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Domestic <xex>prolusions</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her presence was in some measure a restraint on the worthy divine,
whose <qex>prolusion</qex> lasted.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

